I"Q<p>In crypto jargon, we say <strong>hodl</strong> instead of “hold”, as in “hold crypto”.</p>

<p>The term “hodl” is not an acronym.</p>

<h3 id="original-hodl-post">Original HODL Post</h3>

<p>Hodl is a misspelling of “hold” that comes from a now legendary bitcointalk.org post made in 2013 by a drunk OP.</p>

<p>In the hodl’s original post (below), OP is lamenting he did not sell his BTC before a price decline to rebuy at the bottom. He explains he’s not a good trader and therefore makes a public commitment to hodling.</p>

<p><a target="_blank" href="https://res.cloudinary.com/atnetcloud/image/upload/c_lpad,h_360,w_700/v1601967880/atnet/_glossary/hodl_ypbiay.jpg" title="AltcoinTrading.NET - "><figure class="border"><amp-img itemprop="image" src="https://res.cloudinary.com/atnetcloud/image/upload/c_lpad,h_360,w_700/v1601967880/atnet/_glossary/hodl_ypbiay.jpg" alt="" title="AltcoinTrading.NET - " layout="responsive" width="700px" height="360px"></amp-img></figure></a></p>

<p>Hodl therefore does not stand for ‘hold on for dear life’, but the idea is pretty similar to that.</p>

